<div id="review_3798455191" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3798455191" />
    <a title="Gina" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4893960-gina"><img alt="Gina" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1541301287p2/4893960.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3798455191?book_show_action=true">Jan 27, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gina" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gina" href="/user/show/4893960-gina">Gina</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/11236537-bright-lights-big-city">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4893960-gina?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4893960-gina?shelf=good-for-book-club">good-for-book-club</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4893960-gina?shelf=classic">classic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4893960-gina?shelf=new-classic">new-classic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4893960-gina?shelf=urban">urban</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3798455191" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2682139272303136283">I&apos;ve seen this described as both an American and New York iconic/quintessential novel. That didn&apos;t encourage me to read it as such, but it did cause me to add it to my TBR list where it&apos;s been languishing for years. I don&apos;t get very excited for literary fiction or character studies with open ended points, but since Goodreads makes it way too annoying to try and delete things off my &quot;want to read&quot; shelf, it was finally time to clear it out. <br/>It is a brilliant use of second person narrative. That&apos;s</span>
  <span id="freeText2682139272303136283" style="display:none">I've seen this described as both an American and New York iconic/quintessential novel. That didn't encourage me to read it as such, but it did cause me to add it to my TBR list where it's been languishing for years. I don't get very excited for literary fiction or character studies with open ended points, but since Goodreads makes it way too annoying to try and delete things off my "want to read" shelf, it was finally time to clear it out. <br />It is a brilliant use of second person narrative. That's not something a reader sees everyday. I also appreciated how it is both a character study of a person navigating the Manhattan party scene in the 1980's as well as a study of the scene itself. Unfortunately, while I found the writing impeccable, I didn't relate to the characters or story in any meaningful way. McInerney captures (at least I can assume he did given other reviews but I lack direct knowledge) the zeitgeist of being a 20-something in the age of endless coke and clubbing with equal parts sympathy and self-destruction. I'm torn on the ending, as I think it leaves whether it is a positive or negative ending to the reader, and I'm still not sure which way I would argue. I don't think I'm going to waste much time thinking about it. As a niche slice of life at a given point in American history in a very specific place, I can buy the iconic label. Reading it now in 2021, I'm turned off by the ennui of first world problems and self-destructive response to loss. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2682139272303136283" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


